flowRoot.flowPara: Time spent and left of transient states in stationary populations

In stationary multistate populations, the distribution of individuals in a given state by time spent continuously in that state is identical to (or symmetrical to) the distribution by time left in that state. We aim to prove this symmetry.

This might be useful to know because if you can estimate one of these distributions then you can infer the other. Specifically, it might be helpful to devise a way to estimate the unobserved age pattern of onset for health conditions.
Any R code or LaTeX related to this work is available in a public repository, including while in development:
https://github.com/timriffe/TransientSymmetry

Stationary populations are more symmetrical with respect to time spent and left than has been previously described. We give an intuitive proof that the distributions of time spent and left are equal within states in stationary populations. We hope that this relationship may inspire new measurement approaches. We think that that researchers working with censored or truncated data or any kind of multistate models should be generally aware of this equality in case it may come in handy as a heuristic.

The transient tenure symmetry we describe here is also tractable in stable populations, but we have not investigated this extension in detail. Future research, potentially more sophisticated simulations, should aim to establish the impact of departures from stationarity and suggest bounds of usability for this relationship.
Francisco Villavicencio and Tim Riffe (2016) Symmetries between life lived and left in finite stationary populations, Demographic Research. V. 34, pp 381-398

flowRoot.flowPara: This setup implies a finite number of possible life trajectories (discrete sequences of states). Specifically, we get 126 possible trajectories for this model (left). Each trajectory has a single probability of occurring, allowing us to weight each possible trajectory to determine the stationary population composition (middle).

If each mortality schedule is closed out with 1, then the sum of the probabilities of all possible trajectories is 1. Under stationarity this composition is fixed. That means everything about it is fixed.
Matrix-based models calculate the fundamental matrix, which has a fixed age-state occupancy composition like this.
The trajectory composition can be collapsed in other ways, though, to learn something about episode structure.
